stores become depleted during exercise","Fats cannot be metabolised during intense exercise"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe shift from fat to carbohydrate metabolism during increased exercise intensity occurs because \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbohydrates generate ATP more rapidly than fats\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows for quicker energy supply to meet the demands of high-intensity exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbohydrates do require less oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E per ATP produced, this is not the primary reason for the metabolic shift. \u003Cstrong\u003EFats actually yield more ATP\u003C/strong\u003E per gram than carbohydrates, making the option about carbohydrates yielding more total ATP incorrect. \u003Cstrong\u003EFat stores\u003C/strong\u003E are abundant and \u003Cstrong\u003Edo not become significantly depleted\u003C/strong\u003E during exercise. Additionally, \u003Cstrong\u003Efats can still be metabolised during intense exercise, j\u003C/strong\u003Eust at a slower rate compared to carbohydrates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased adrenaline levels during high-intensity exercise also promote carbohydrate metabolism, further contributing to this shift.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The \u0027crossover\u0027 concept in exercise physiology describes the shift from fat to carbohydrate metabolism as exercise intensity increases.","This shift occurs because carbohydrates can be metabolised more rapidly than fats, providing quicker ATP production.","Increased exercise intensity leads to higher adrenaline levels, which promote carbohydrate metabolism."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness E, Barness LA, Farrell PM, editors. Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. Amsterdam: IOS Press; 2017.","Lanham-New SA, Macdonald IA, Roche HM, editors. Nutrition and metabolism. Hoboken: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2011.","Roche HM, Macdonald IA, Schols AM, Lanham-New SA, editors. Nutrition and metabolism. Hoboken: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2024.","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75.","Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, editors. Robbins basic pathology e-book. Amsterdam: Elsevier Health Science; 2012.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96624"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17986"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96624"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T14:02:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T14:02:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10700"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114621"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retriev